\newcommand{\Z}{$\zeta$}

\section*{Boundary quantities}

\emph{Boundary quantities} in the forward model are computed at a point on
the path that intersects a constant-pressure (\Z) surface, or at points
between those boundaries needed for Gauss-Legendre (GL) quadrature.

\begin{itemize}

\item Temperature (Kelvin)

\item Pressure ($\zeta = -\log_{10} P$, where $P$ is hectopascals or
      millibars)

\item Geodetic height (km)

\item Geocentric height (km)

\item Geodetic orbit angle $\phi$ (radians)

\item Mixing ratio $f^k$ ($k$ is the species index)

\item Absorption cross section $\beta^k$

\item Absorption coefficient $\alpha = \sum_k \beta^k f^k$

\item Derivatives of $\alpha$ with respect to mixing ratio or temperature

\item Path geometry derivatives $\frac{\text{d}s}{\text{d}h}$ and
      $\frac{\text{d}h}{\text{d}\zeta}$.  $\frac{\text{d}s}{\text{d}h}$ is
      set to zero at the tangent point even though there is an infinite
      square-root singularity there: $s = \sqrt{h^2 - h_T^2}$ and
      therefore $\frac{\text{d}s}{\text{d}h} = \frac{h}s$.

\end{itemize}

Boundary quantities are represented on two kinds of grids.

\subsection*{Coarse grid quantities}

The \emph{coarse grid} consists only of the points where the path
intersects a (\Z) surface that is in one of the \Z\ grids for temperature
or some species.  The names of coarse-grid quantities frequently end with
{\tt _c}.  On the coarse grid, the tangent point is represented twice.

\subsection*{Fine grid quantities}

There are three kinds of \emph{fine grid}.  The names of fine-grid
quantities frequently end with {\tt _f}.

\begin{enumerate}

\item The coarse grid, together with intermediate points needed for GL
      quadrature.  The tangent point is represented twice, with space for
      points for GL quadrature between them, but the intervening GL points
      are not used.  They are included to make index calculations easier.

\item Only all the intermediate points that might be needed for
      GL quadrature.

\item Only the intermediate points where integrands for GL quadrature are
      actually needed.

\end{enumerate}

\section*{Layer quantities}

\emph{Layer quantities} in the forward model represent something about a
layer between two points on the coarse grid.  Before the tangent point,
the layer index $j$ refers to the layer between coarse-grid boundary
points $j-1$ and $j$.  After the tangent point, the layer index $j$ refers
to the layer between coarse-grid boundary points $j$ and $j+1$.

\begin{itemize}

\item {\tt del_s} = $\delta s_j =
      \left\{ \begin{array}{l}
        s_j - s_{j-1} \text{ before the tangent point} \\
        s_{j+1} - s_j \text{ after the tangent point} \\
        \end{array} \right. $

\item {\tt del_zeta} = $\delta \zeta_j =
      \left\{ \begin{array}{l}
        \frac12(\zeta_j - \zeta_{j-1}) \text{ before the tangent point} \\
        \frac12(\zeta_{j+1} - \zeta_j) \text{ after the tangent point} \\
        \end{array} \right. $ \\[3pt]
       The factor of $\frac12$ is to compensate for the GL points computed
       on $-1 \,\cdots\, +1$, so the GL weights sum to 2.

\item {\tt incoptdepth} = Incremental optical depth$_j$ = \\[3pt]
      $\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
        \int_{s_{j-1}}^{s_j} \alpha(s) \, \text{d} s \text{ before the
          tangent point} \\
          \\
        \int_{s_j}^{s_{j+1}} \alpha(s) \, \text{d} s \text{ after the
          tangent point} \\
        \end{array} \right. $ \\[3pt]
      at first, for preliminary calculations, then \\[3pt]
      $\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
        \int_{\zeta_{j-1}}^{\zeta_j} \alpha(\zeta) \,
          \frac{\text{d}s}{\text{d}h}\,
          \frac{\text{d}h}{\text{d}\zeta}\, \text{d} \zeta \text{ before the
          tangent point} \\
          \\
        \int_{\zeta_j}^{\zeta_{j+1}} \alpha(\zeta) \,
          \frac{\text{d}s}{\text{d}h}\,
          \frac{\text{d}h}{\text{d}\zeta}\, \text{d} \zeta \text{ after the
          tangent point} \\
        \end{array} \right. $ \\[3pt]
      For layers that do not need GL, a trapezoidal estimate is used.

\item {\tt Do_GL(j)} = $\left\{ \begin{array}{l}
      \text{ before the tangent point, layer from } j-1 \text{ to } j 
      \text{ needs GL} \\
      \text{ after the tangent point, layer from } j \text{ to } j+1 
      \text{ needs GL} \\
      \end{array} \right. $

\end{itemize}

